, 
<figureCitation id="DB852A6E3D1DFF40CD85FE565CFA44C0" box="[459,490,438,463]" captionStart="FIGURES 24 – 26" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1816,1838]" captionTargetBox="[151,1372,646,1750]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,589,1795]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 24 – 26. Hoplia dubia species group. Comparison between the shape of protoracic tarsi (right leg, ventral view), length uniform. 24, Hoplia dubia (Marina di Vecchiano); 25, H. meridiana (R. N. O. Bosco Pantano di Policoro); 26, H. messapia (Cesine, Le Vernole). A stouter structure, with broader tarsomeres and claw, is evident in H. meridiana (courtesy of Daniele Baiocchi and Lara Gallina)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/891728/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="210">26</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="DB852A6E3D1DFF40CDBBFE575F2D44C0" box="[501,573,439,463]" captionStart="FIGURES 34 – 38" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1939,1961]" captionTargetBox="[212,1389,193,1921]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[212,1389,193,1921]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 34 – 38. Hoplia messapia in nature from Vernole, Le Cesine. 34, male on a Tamarix inflorescence, 20. V. 2011 (courtesy of Maurizio Pavesi); 35 – 37, males clustering on the top of grasses and on dry Juncus infructescences, 21. V. 2011 (courtesy of Maurizio Bollino); 38, habitat of the species, 7. VI. 2003 (courtesy of Giuseppe De Matteis)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/891736/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="210">34–37</figureCitation>
